[[File:Piedra del Aguila Angol, Chile.jpg|250px|thumb|''[[Araucaria araucana|Araucarias]]'' growing on top of rocks of the Coastal Batholith, [[Cordillera de Nahuelbuta]].]] The '''Coastal Batholith of central Chile''' is a group of [[pluton]]s in the [[Chilean Coast Range]] of [[Central Chile]] appearing contiguously from 33° S to 38° S.<ref name=Deckartetal2014>{{cite journal |last=Deckart |first=Katja |last2=Hervé |first2=Francisco |last3=Fanning |first3=C. Mark |last5=Calderón |first5=Mauricio |last4=Ramírez |first4=Valeria |last6=Godoy |first6=Estanislao |author-link2=Francisco Hervé |date=2014 |title=U-Pb Geochronology and Hf-O Isotopes of zircons from the Pennsylvanian Coastal Batholith, South-Central Chile |url=http://www.andeangeology.cl/index.php/revista1/article/view/V41n1-a03/html |journal=[[Andean Geology]] |publisher= |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages= |doi=10.5027/andgeoV41n1-a03 |access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=KleimanJapas2009/> At a latitude of 40° S an outlying group of plutons of the [[batholith]] appear in a more eastward position in the [[Andes]].<ref name=Deckartetal2014/>
Together with the [[Elqui-Limarí Batholith]] and the [[Colangüil Batholith]], the Coastal Batholith of central Chile is a remnant of the [[volcanic arc]]s that erupted the volcanic material of the [[Choiyoi Group]]. During the [[Permian]] the zone of arc magmatism moved from the Coastal Batholith 350 km inland reaching [[San Rafael, Argentina|San Rafael]] about 280 million years ago.<ref name=KleimanJapas2009>{{cite journal |last=Kleiman |first=Laura E. |last2=Japas |first2=María S. |date=2009 |title=The Choiyoi volcanic province at 34°S–36°S (San Rafael, Mendoza, Argentina): Implications for the Late Palaeozoic evolution of the southwestern margin of Gondwana |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Laura_Kleiman/publication/241406241_The_Choiyoi_volcanic_province_at_34S-36S_%28San_Rafael_Mendoza_Argentina%29_Implications_for_the_Late_Palaeozoic_evolution_of_the_southwestern_margin_of_Gondwana/links/546b47370cf2f5eb18091754.pdf |journal=[[Tectonophysics (journal)|Tectonophysics]] |publisher= |volume=473 |issue= |pages=283–299 |doi= |access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> The batholith is emplaced amidst [[metamorphic rock]]s belonging to a [[Paleozoic]] [[accretionary prism|accretionary complex]]. The northern parts are of the batholith are themselves intruded by [[Jurassic]] [[gabbro]]s.<ref name=Deckartetal2014/>
Rocks of the batholith belong to the [[calc-alkaline magma series]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hervé |first1=F.|last2=Faundez |first2=V. |last3=Calderón |first3=M. |last4=Massonne |first4=H.-J. |last5=Willner |first5=A.P. |author-link=Francisco Hervé |editor-last1=Moreno |editor-first1=Teresa|editor-last2=Gibbons |editor-first2=Wes |title=The Geology of Chile |publisher=[[Geological Society of London]] |date=2007 |pages=7–20 |chapter=Metamorphic and plutonic basement complexes |isbn=}}</ref>
