{{Infobox Mars crater | name = Dromore (crater) | image = Detail of Maja Valles Flow.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = Great amounts of water were required to carry out the erosion shown in this Viking image. Image is located in [[Lunae Palus quadrangle]]. The erosion shaped the ejecta around Dromore. | coordinates = {{coord|20.1|N|49.7|W|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | discoverer = | diameter = 14.8 [[Kilometer|km]] | eponym = Dromore, a common placename in [[Ireland]] (from [[Irish language|Irish]] ''Droim Mór'' meaning "big ridge") }}
'''Dromore''' is a [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Mars]], located within the outflow channel [[Maja Valles]] in the [[Lunae Palus quadrangle]] at 20.1 N and 49.7 W. It measures 14.8 kilometers in diameter and was named after a town in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{gpn|1641}}</ref>
Dromore is famous for showing clear evidence that it was affected by floods of water which broke through dams, carved deep valleys, and eroded grooves into bedrock. <gallery> Wikidromore.jpg|Dromore Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]). </gallery>
